# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detonator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta drew admiration from Napoleon Bonaparte for his invention, and was invited to the Institute of France to demonstrate his invention to the members of the institute.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Throughout his life, Volta enjoyed a certain amount of closeness with the emperor who conferred upon him numerous honours.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta held the chair of experimental physics at the University of Pavia for nearly 40 years and was widely idolised by his students.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Despite his professional success, Volta was inclined towards domestic life and this was more apparent in his later years when he tended to live secluded from public life and more for the sake of his family.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He died in 1827 from a series of illnesses which began in 1823.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The SI unit of electric potential is named the volt in his honour.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta was born in Como, a town in northern Italy, on 18 February 1745.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] His father, Filippo Volta, was of noble lineage.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] His mother, Donna Maddalena, came from the family of the Inzaghis.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1794, Volta married an aristocratic lady also from Como, Teresa Peregrini, with whom he raised three sons: Zanino, Flaminio, and Luigi.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1774, he became a professor of physics at the Royal School in Como.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] A year later, he improved and popularised the electrophorus, a device that produced static electricity.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] His promotion of it was so extensive that he is often credited with its invention, even though a machine operating on the same principle was described in 1762 by the Swedish experimenter Johan Wilcke.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1777, he travelled through Switzerland, where he befriended the physicist and mountaineer H.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In the years between 1776 and 1778, Volta studied the chemistry of gases.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He researched and discovered methane after reading a paper by Benjamin Franklin of the United States on "flammable air".
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In November 1776, he found methane in the marshes of Angera on Lake Maggiore, and by 1778 he managed to isolate it.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He devised experiments such as the ignition of methane by an electric spark in a closed vessel.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta also studied what we now call electrical capacitance, developing separate means to study both electrical potential difference (*V*) and charge (*Q*), and discovering that for a given object, they are proportional.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] This is called Volta's Law of Capacitance, and for this work, the unit of electrical potential has been named the volt.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1779, he became a professor of experimental physics at the University of Pavia, a chair that he occupied for almost 40 years.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta's lectures were so crowded with students that the subsequent emperor Joseph II ordered the construction (based on a project by Leopold Pollack) of a new "physical theatre", today the "Aula Volta".
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Furthermore, the emperor granted Volta substantial funding to equip the physics cabinet with instruments, purchased by Volta in England and France.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] At the University History Museum of the University of Pavia there are 150 of them, used by Alessandro Volta.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Luigi Galvani, an Italian physicist, discovered something he named "animal electricity" when two different metals were connected in series with a frog's leg and to one another.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta realised that the frog's leg served as both a conductor of electricity (what we would now call an electrolyte) and as a detector of electricity.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He also understood that the frog's legs were irrelevant to the electric current, which was caused by the two differing metals.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He replaced the frog's leg with brine-soaked paper and detected the flow of electricity by other means familiar to him from his previous studies.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] This may be called Volta's Law of the electrochemical series.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1800, as the result of a professional disagreement over the galvanic response advocated by Galvani, Volta invented the voltaic pile, an early electric battery, which produced a steady electric current.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta had determined that the most effective pair of dissimilar metals to produce electricity was zinc and copper.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Initially, he experimented with individual cells in series, each cell being a wine goblet filled with brine into which the two dissimilar electrodes were dipped.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The voltaic pile replaced the goblets with cardboard soaked in brine.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In announcing his invention of the voltaic pile, Volta paid tribute to the influences of William Nicholson, Tiberius Cavallo, and Abraham Bennet.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The battery made by Volta is credited as one of the first electrochemical cells.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] It consists of two electrodes: one made of zinc, the other of copper.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The electrolyte is either sulphuric acid mixed with water or a form of saltwater brine.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The electrolyte exists in the form 2 H+ and SO2−4.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Zinc metal, which is higher in the electrochemical series than both copper and hydrogen, is oxidized to zinc cations (Zn2+) and creates electrons that move to the copper electrode.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The positively charged hydrogen ions (protons) capture electrons from the copper electrode, forming bubbles of hydrogen gas, H2.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] This makes the zinc rod the negative electrode and the copper rod the positive electrode.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Thus, there are two terminals, and an electric current will flow if they are connected.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Copper metal does not react, but rather it functions as a catalyst for the hydrogen-gas formation and an electrode for the electric current.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The sulphate anion (SO2−4) does not undergo any chemical reaction either, but migrates to the zinc anode to compensate for the charge of the zinc cations formed there.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] However, this cell also has some disadvantages.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] It is unsafe to handle, since sulphuric acid, even if diluted, can be hazardous.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Also, the power of the cell diminishes over time because the hydrogen gas is not released.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Instead, it accumulates on the surface of the copper electrode and forms a barrier between the metal and the electrolyte solution.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1809, Volta became an associated member of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In honour of his work, Volta was made a count by Napoleon Bonaparte in 1810.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta retired in 1819 to his estate in Camnago, a *frazione* of Como, Italy, now named "Camnago Volta" in his honour.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] He died there on 5 March 1827, just after his 82nd birthday.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta's remains were buried in Camnago Volta.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta's legacy is celebrated by the Tempio Voltiano memorial located in the public gardens by the lake.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] There is also a museum that was built in his honour, which exhibits some of the equipment that Volta used to conduct experiments.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Nearby stands the Villa Olmo, which houses the Voltian Foundation, an organization promoting scientific activities.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta carried out his experimental studies and produced his first inventions near Como.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In the Old Campus of the University of Pavia, there is the classroom (Aula Volta) commissioned by Emperor Joseph II to Leopoldo Pollack in 1787 for the lectures of Alessandro Volta, while in the University History Museum there are many scientific instruments that belonged to Volta.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In 1927, an international physics conference, the Como Conference was held at Lake Como for the 100th anniversary of his death.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] His image was depicted on the Italian Lire 10,000 note (1990–1997) along with a sketch of his voltaic pile.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] In late 2017, Nvidia announced a new workstation-focused GPU microarchitecture called Volta.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] The electric eel species *Electrophorus voltai*, described in 2019 as the strongest bioelectricity producer in nature, was named after Volta.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Volta was raised as a Catholic and for all of his life continued to maintain his belief.
[src:detonator/alessandro-volta] Because he was not ordained a clergyman as his family expected, he was sometimes accused of being irreligious and some people have speculated about his possible unbelief, stressing that "he did not join the Church", or that he virtually "ignored the church's call".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Born into the prominent Nobel family in Stockholm, Nobel displayed an early aptitude for science and learning, particularly in chemistry and languages; he became fluent in six languages and filed his first patent at the age of 24.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He embarked on many business ventures with his family, most notably owning the company Bofors—which was an iron and steel producer that he had developed into a major manufacturer of cannons and other armaments.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel's most famous invention, dynamite, was an explosive made using nitroglycerin, which was patented in 1867.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He further invented gelignite in 1875 and ballistite in 1887.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Upon his death, Nobel donated his fortune to a foundation to fund the Nobel Prizes, which annually recognize those who have "conferred the greatest benefit to humankind".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The synthetic element nobelium was named after him, and his name and legacy also survive in companies such as Dynamit Nobel and AkzoNobel, which descend from mergers with companies he founded.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel was elected a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, which, pursuant to his will, is responsible for choosing the Nobel laureates in Physics and in Chemistry.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Alfred Nobel was born in Stockholm, Sweden, on 21 October 1833.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He was the third son of Immanuel Nobel (1801–1872), an inventor and engineer, and Andriette Nobel (née Ahlsell 1805–1889).
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The couple married in 1827 and had eight children.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The family was impoverished, and only Alfred and his three brothers survived beyond their childhood.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Through his father, Alfred Nobel was a descendant of the Swedish scientist Olaus Rudbeck (1630–1702).
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel's father was an alumnus of the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm and was an engineer and inventor who built bridges and buildings and experimented with different ways of blasting rocks.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He encouraged and taught Nobel from a young age.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Following various business failures caused by the loss of some barges of building material, Immanuel Nobel was forced into bankruptcy.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel's father moved to Saint Petersburg, then part of the Russian Empire, and grew successful there as a manufacturer of machine tools and explosives.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He invented the veneer lathe, which made possible the production of modern plywood, and started work on the naval mine.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1842, the family joined him in the city.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Now prosperous, his parents were able to send Nobel to private tutors, and the boy excelled in his studies, particularly in chemistry and languages, achieving fluency in English, French, German, and Russian.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] For 18 months, from 1841 to 1842, Nobel attended the Jacobs Apologistic School in Stockholm, his only schooling; he never attended university.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel gained proficiency in Swedish, French, Russian, English, German, and Italian.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He also developed sufficient literary skill to write poetry in English.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] His *Nemesis* is a prose tragedy in four acts about the Italian noblewoman Beatrice Cenci.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] It was printed while he was dying, but the entire stock was destroyed immediately after his death, except for three copies, being regarded as scandalous and blasphemous.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] It was published in Sweden in 2003 and has been translated into Slovenian, French, Italian, and Spanish.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] As a young man, Nobel studied with chemist Nikolai Zinin; then, in 1850, he went to Paris to further the work.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] There he met Ascanio Sobrero, who had synthesized nitroglycerin three years before.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Sobrero strongly opposed the use of nitroglycerin because it was unpredictable, exploding when subjected to variable heat or pressure.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] But Nobel became interested in finding a way to control and use nitroglycerin as a commercially usable explosive; it had much more power than gunpowder.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1851 at age 18, he went to the United States for one year to study, working for a short period under Swedish-American inventor John Ericsson, who designed the American Civil War ironclad, USS *Monitor*.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel filed his first patent, an English patent for a gas meter, in 1857, while his first Swedish patent, which he received in 1863, was on "ways to prepare gunpowder".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The family factory produced armaments for the Crimean War (1853–1856), but had difficulty switching back to regular domestic production when the fighting ended and they filed for bankruptcy.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1859, Nobel's father left his factory in the care of the second son, Ludvig Nobel (1831–1888), who greatly improved the business.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel and his parents returned to Sweden from Russia, and Nobel devoted himself to the study of explosives, and especially to the safe manufacture and use of nitroglycerin.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel invented a detonator in 1863, and in 1865 designed the blasting cap.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] On 3 September 1864, a shed used for preparation of nitroglycerin exploded at the factory in Heleneborg, Stockholm, Sweden, killing five people, including Nobel's younger brother Emil.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He was then deprived of his license to produce explosives.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Fazed by the accident, Nobel founded the company Nitroglycerin AB in Vinterviken so that he could continue to work in a more isolated area.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel invented dynamite in 1867, a substance easier and safer to handle than the more unstable nitroglycerin.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Dynamite was patented in the US and the UK and was used extensively in mining and the building of transport networks internationally.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1875, Nobel invented gelignite, more stable and powerful than dynamite, and in 1887, patented ballistite, a predecessor of cordite.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel was elected a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in 1884, the same institution that would later select laureates for two of the Nobel prizes, and he received an honorary doctorate from Uppsala University in 1893.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel's brothers Ludvig and Robert founded the oil company Branobel and became hugely rich in their own right.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel invested in these and amassed great wealth through the development of these new oil regions.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] It operated mainly in Baku, Azerbaijan, but also in Cheleken, Turkmenistan.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] During his life, Nobel was issued 355 patents internationally, and by his death, his business had established more than 90 explosives and armament factories, despite his apparently pacifist character.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel found that when nitroglycerin was incorporated in an absorbent inert substance like *kieselguhr* (diatomaceous earth) it became safer and more convenient to handle, and this mixture he patented in 1867 as "dynamite".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel demonstrated his explosive for the first time that year, at a quarry in Redhill, Surrey, England.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel later combined nitroglycerin with various nitrocellulose compounds, similar to collodion, but settled on a more efficient recipe combining another nitrate explosive, and obtained a transparent, jelly-like substance, which was a more powerful explosive than dynamite.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Gelignite, or blasting gelatin, as it was named, was patented in 1876; and was followed by a host of similar combinations, modified by the addition of potassium nitrate and various other substances.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Gelignite was more stable, powerful, transportable and conveniently formed to fit into bored holes, like those used in drilling and mining, than the previously used compounds.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] It was adopted as the standard technology for mining in the "Age of Engineering", bringing Nobel a great amount of financial success, though at a cost to his health.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] An offshoot of this research resulted in Nobel's invention of ballistite, the precursor of many modern smokeless powder explosives and still used as a rocket propellant.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] There is a well-known story about the origin of the Nobel Prize, although historians have been unable to verify it, and some dismiss the story as a myth.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1888, the death of his brother Ludvig supposedly caused several newspapers to publish obituaries of Alfred in error.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] One French newspaper condemned him for his invention of military explosives—in many versions of the story, dynamite is quoted, although this was mainly used for civilian applications—and this is said to have brought about his decision to leave a better legacy after his death.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The obituary supposedly stated, **Le marchand de la mort est mort** ("The merchant of death is dead"), and according to the myth went on to say, "Dr.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Alfred Nobel, who became rich by finding ways to kill more people faster than ever before, died yesterday." Nobel read the obituary and was appalled at the idea that he would be remembered in this way.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] His decision to posthumously donate the majority of his wealth to found the Nobel Prize has been credited to him wanting to leave behind a better legacy.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] However, it has been questioned whether or not the obituary in question actually existed.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] An actual obituary (pictured) stated "A man who can only with the utmost difficulty be considered a benefactor of mankind has died yesterday at Cannes.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel was Swedish." It was published on the first page of the Figaro on the 15th of April 1888 and retracted the next day.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] On 27 November 1895, at the Swedish-Norwegian Club in Paris, Nobel signed his last will and set aside the bulk of his estate to establish the Nobel Prizes, to be awarded annually without distinction of nationality.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] After taxes and bequests to individuals, Nobel's will allocated 94% of his total assets, 31,225,000 Swedish kronor, to establish the five Nobel Prizes.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] By 2022, the foundation had approximately 6 billion Swedish Kronor of invested capital.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The formulation for the literary prize being given for a work "in an ideal direction" (**i idealisk riktning** in Swedish) is cryptic and has caused much confusion.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] For many years, the Swedish Academy interpreted "ideal" as "idealistic" (**idealistisk**) and used it as a reason not to give the prize to important but less romantic authors, such as Henrik Ibsen and Leo Tolstoy.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] This interpretation has since been revised, and the prize has been awarded to, for example, Dario Fo and José Saramago, who do not belong to the camp of literary idealism.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] There was room for interpretation by the bodies he had named for deciding on the physical sciences and chemistry prizes, given that he had not consulted them before making the will.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In his one-page testament, he stipulated that the money go to discoveries or inventions in the physical sciences and to discoveries or improvements in chemistry.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He had opened the door to technological awards, but had not left instructions on how to deal with the distinction between science and technology.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Since the deciding bodies he had chosen were more concerned with the former, the prizes went to scientists more often than engineers, technicians, or other inventors.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Sweden's central bank Sveriges Riksbank celebrated its 300th anniversary in 1968 by donating a large sum of money to the Nobel Foundation to be used to set up a sixth prize in the field of economics in honor of Alfred Nobel.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 2001, Alfred Nobel's great-great-nephew, Peter Nobel (born 1931), asked the Bank of Sweden to differentiate its award to economists given "in Alfred Nobel's memory" from the five other awards.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] This request added to the controversy over whether the Bank of Sweden Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel is actually a legitimate "Nobel Prize".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In his letters to his mistress, Hess, Nobel described constant pain, debilitating migraines, and "paralyzing" fatigue, leading some to believe that he suffered from fibromyalgia.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] However, his concerns at the time were dismissed as hypochondria, leading to further depression.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] By 1895, Nobel had developed angina pectoris.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] On 27 November 1895, he finalized his will and testament, leaving most of his wealth in trust, unbeknownst to his family, to fund the Nobel Prize awards.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] On 10 December 1896, he suffered a stroke/intracerebral hemorrhage and was first partially paralyzed and then died, aged 63.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He is buried in Norra begravningsplatsen in Stockholm.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Based on his experimentation with explosives, his strenuous work habits, and the decline in his health at the end of the 1870s, some hypothesize that nitroglycerine poisoning was a contributing factor to his death.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel was Lutheran and, during his years living in Paris, he regularly attended the Church of Sweden Abroad led by pastor Nathan Söderblom, who received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1930.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He was an agnostic in youth and became an atheist later in life, though he still donated generously to the Church.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel remained a solitary character, given to periods of depression.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] He never married, although his biographers note that he had at least three loves.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] His first love was in Russia with a girl named Alexandra, who rejected his marriage proposal.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1876, Austro-Bohemian Countess Bertha von Suttner became his secretary, but she left him after a brief stay to marry her previous lover, Baron Arthur Gundaccar von Suttner.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Her contact with Nobel was brief, yet she corresponded with him until he died in 1896, and probably influenced his decision to include the Nobel Peace Prize in his will.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] She was awarded the 1905 Nobel Peace prize "for her sincere peace activities".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel's longest-lasting romance was an 18-year relationship with Sofija Hess from Celje, whom he met in 1876 in Baden bei Wien, where she worked as an employee in a flower shop that catered to wealthy clientele.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The extent of their relationship was revealed by a collection of 221 letters sent by Nobel to Hess over 15 years.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] At the time that they met, Nobel was 43 years old while Hess was 26.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Their relationship, which was not merely platonic, ended when she became pregnant with the child of another man, although Nobel continued to support her financially until Hess married the father of her child as to avoid her being ostracized.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In the letters sent to Hess, Nobel mentions many times his distaste for not only Hess' Jewish ancestry, but also her family, and makes antisemitic remarks towards Jews as a whole.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Sofie's failure to respond to his antisemitic diatribes is surprising, and far from protesting against Nobel's remarks, she used abusive language against Jews herself and eventually converted to Protestantism in 1894 in a naive attempt to grow closer to Nobel.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Though even with her spiteful remarks against her heritage, Hess was always loyal to her family and supported them financially.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel remarked that she was his "great devourer of banknotes".
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel traveled for much of his business life, maintaining companies in Europe and America.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] From 1865 to 1873, Nobel lived in Krümmel (now in the municipality of Geesthacht, near Hamburg).
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] From 1873 to 1891, he lived in a house on the Avenue de Malakoff in Paris.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1891, after being accused of high treason against France for selling Ballistite to Italy, he moved from Paris to Sanremo, Italy, acquiring Villa Nobel, overlooking the Mediterranean Sea, where he died in 1896.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] In 1894, when he acquired Bofors-Gullspång, the Björkborn Manor was included, where he stayed during the summers.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The *Monument to Alfred Nobel* (Russian: Памятник Альфреду Нобелю, 59°57′39″N 30°20′06″E﻿ / ﻿59.960787°N 30.334905°E﻿ / 59.960787; 30.334905) stands in Saint Petersburg along the Bolshaya Nevka River on the Petrogradskaya Embankment, the street where Nobel's family lived until 1859.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] It was dedicated in 1991 to mark the 90th anniversary of the first Nobel Prize presentation.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Diplomat Thomas Bertelman and Professor Arkady Melua were initiators of the creation of the monument in 1989, and they provided funds for the construction of it.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] The abstract metal sculpture was designed by local artists Sergey Alipov and Pavel Shevchenko, and appears to be an explosion or branches of a tree.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Criticism of Nobel usually focuses on his leading role in the manufacture and sale of arms and ammunitions.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Some people question his motives for his creation of the Nobel Prize, suggesting that he created it in an attempt to improve his reputation.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] For example, the 1984 public artwork *Nobel Metamorphoses* in Troisdorf, Germany – at the time the location of the Dynamit Nobel headquarters – contrasts war death statistics to peace prize recipients since the latter's inauguration in 1901 through a critical lens.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Nobel has been criticized by the newspaper Haaretz for antisemitic statements made in letters to his mistress Sofie Hess.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] During the late 1800's and early 1900's, much of Europe was swept up by a strong current of virulent antisemitism.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] Within Nobel's letters are examples of his negative view of people of Jewish ancestry such as Hess's family.
[src:detonator/alfred-nobel] For example, he writes: "In my experience, [Jews] never do anything out of goodwill.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:detonator/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In some languages and regions, terms similar to "apothecary" have survived and denote modern pharmacies or pharmacists.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecaries' investigation of herbal and chemical ingredients was a precursor to the modern sciences of chemistry and pharmacology.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In addition to dispensing herbs and medicine, apothecaries offered general medical advice and a range of services that are now performed by other specialist practitioners, such as surgeons and obstetricians.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecary shops sold ingredients and the medicines they prepared wholesale to other medical practitioners, as well as dispensing them to patients.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In 17th-century England, they also controlled the trade in tobacco, which was imported as a medicine.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The term "apothecary" derives from the Ancient Greek ἀποθήκη (*apothḗkē*, "a repository, storehouse") via Latin *apotheca* ("repository, storehouse, warehouse", cf.
[src:detonator/apothecary] *bodega* and *boutique*), Medieval Latin *apothecarius* ("storekeeper"), and eventually Old French *apotecaire*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In some European and other languages, the term is current and used to designate a pharmacist/chemist, such as Dutch and German *Apotheker*, Hungarian *patikus*, Irish *poitigéir*, Latvian *aptiekārs* and Luxembourgish *Apdikter*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The word in Indonesian is *apoteker*, which was borrowed from the Dutch *apotheker*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In Yiddish the word is אַפּטייק *apteyk*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Use of the term in the names of businesses varies with time and location.
[src:detonator/apothecary] It is generally an Americanism, though some areas of the United States use it to invoke an experience of nostalgic revival and it has been used for a wide variety of businesses; while in other areas such as California its use is restricted to licensed pharmacies.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In Exodus 30:25 of the Hebrew Bible, a practice similar to apothecary is mentioned.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The profession of apothecary can be dated back at least to 2600 BC to ancient Babylon, which provides one of the earliest records of the practice of the apothecary.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Clay tablets have been found with medical texts recording symptoms, prescriptions, and directions for compounding.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The Papyrus Ebers from ancient Egypt, written c.
[src:detonator/apothecary] 1500 BC, contains a collection of more than 800 prescriptions with over 700 drugs.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In ancient India, the *Sushruta Samhita*, a compendium on the practice of medicine and medical formulations, has been traced back to the 1st century BC.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The *Shennong Ben Cao Jing*, a Chinese book on agriculture and medicinal plants (3rd century AD), is considered a foundational material for Chinese medicine and herbalism and became an important source for Chinese apothecaries.
[src:detonator/apothecary] The book, which documented 365 treatments, had a focus on roots and grass.
[src:detonator/apothecary] It had treatments which came from minerals, roots, grass, and animals.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Many of the mentioned drugs and their uses are still followed today.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Ginseng's use as a sexual stimulant and aid for erectile dysfunction stems from this book.
[src:detonator/apothecary] *Ma huang*, an herb first mentioned in the book, led to the introduction of the drug ephedrine into modern medicine.
[src:detonator/apothecary] According to Sharif Kaf al-Ghazal and S.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Hadzovic, apothecary shops existed during the Middle Ages in Baghdad, operated by pharmacists in 754 during the Abbasid Caliphate and Islamic Golden Age.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecaries were also active in Al-Andalus by the 11th century.
[src:detonator/apothecary] By the end of the 14th century, Geoffrey Chaucer (c.
[src:detonator/apothecary] During the Italian Renaissance, Italian nuns became a prominent source for medicinal needs.
[src:detonator/apothecary] At first, they used their knowledge of non-curative uses in the convents to reinforce the sanctity of religion among their sisters.
[src:detonator/apothecary] As they progressed in skill, they began to expand their field to generate profit.
[src:detonator/apothecary] This profit they used towards their charitable goals.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Because of their eventual spread to urban society, these religious women gained roles of public significance beyond the spiritual realm, writes S.T.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Later, apothecaries led by nuns spread across the Italian peninsula.
[src:detonator/apothecary] From the 15th century to the 16th century, the apothecary gained the status of a skilled practitioner.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In London, the apothecaries merited their own livery company, the Worshipful Society of Apothecaries, founded in 1617.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Its roots, however, go back much earlier to the Guild of Pepperers formed in London in 1180.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Similarly in Ireland, apothecaries were organized before 1446.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In Ireland and Great Britain, they were allowed to diagnose diseases in addition to their compounding and dispensing roles, becoming regulated general medical practitioners and the forerunners of general practitioners there.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Oftentimes, women, who were prohibited from entering medical school, became apothecaries, taking away business from male physicians.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In 1865, Elizabeth Garrett Anderson was the first woman to be licensed to practice medicine in Britain by passing the examination of the Society of Apothecaries.
[src:detonator/apothecary] By the end of the 19th century, the medical professions had taken on their current institutional form, with defined roles for physicians and surgeons, and the role of the apothecary was more narrowly conceived, as that of pharmacist or chemist.
[src:detonator/apothecary] In German-speaking countries, such as Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, pharmacies or chemist stores are still called apothecaries or, in German, *Apotheken*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Thus, a *Pharmazeut* is not always an *Apotheker*.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Magdalena Neff became the first woman to gain a medical qualification in Germany when she studied pharmacy at the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology and later passed the apothecary's examination in 1906.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecaries used their own measurement system, the apothecaries' system, to provide precise weighing of small quantities.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecaries dispensed vials of poisons as well as medicines, and as is still the case, medicines could be either beneficial or harmful if inappropriately used.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Protective methods to prevent accidental ingestion of poisons included the use of specially-shaped containers for potentially poisonous substances such as laudanum.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Apothecary businesses were typically family-run, and wives or other women of the family worked alongside their husbands in the shops, learning the trade themselves.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Women were still not allowed to train or be educated in universities, so this allowed them a chance to learn medical knowledge and healing practices.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Previously, women had some influence over other women's healthcare, such as serving as midwives and providing other feminine care in settings not considered appropriate for males.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Though physicians gave medical advice, they did not make medicine, so they typically sent their patients to particular independent apothecaries, who also provided some medical advice, in particular remedies and healing.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Many recipes for medicines included herbs, minerals, and pieces of animals (meats, fats, skins) that were ingested, made into paste for external use, or used as aromatherapy.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Some of these are similar to natural remedies used today, including catnip, chamomile, fennel, mint, garlic, and witch hazel.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Many other ingredients used in the past such as urine, fecal matter, earwax, human fat, and saliva, are no longer used and are generally considered ineffective or unsanitary.
[src:detonator/apothecary] Trial and error were the main source for finding successful remedies, as little was known about the chemistry of why certain treatments worked.
[src:detonator/apothecary] For instance, it was known that drinking coffee could help cure headaches, but the existence and properties of caffeine itself was still a mystery.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Justice Department's proposal, a Philadelphia court approved a decree on June 13, 1912, that ordered the division of Du Pont Powder Company into three independent entities.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] The decision concluded an anti-monopoly case filed by the United States government against the company under the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] These three new companies, which became independent companies and substantial competitors, were called Hercules Powder Company, Atlas Powder Company, and the du Pont de Nemours Powder Company.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Atlas was officially incorporated on October 18, 1912, in Wilmington, Delaware.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] However, Pierre and Irenee DuPont, president and vice-president of DuPont, still owned large blocks of stock in the company as was in the case of Hercules.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Atlas Powder Company and Hercules competed with DuPont in the manufacture of dynamite and black powder.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] It purchased Giant Powder Company in 1915, which continued to operate a production facility at Point Pinole until 1960.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] By 1919, Atlas Powder Company became a military supplier.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] During the years leading up to World War I, it was also Britain and France's main supplier of explosives.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] It delivered 37 million pounds of ammonium nitrate as well as acids and nitro cotton.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] It became one of the five major companies that served the American munitions market.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] The company worked for the U.S. government.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] An example was its operation of a plant in Maryland, which was built by the United States Ordnance Department.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] This facility produced 452,000 pounds of ammonium nitrate.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Along with Hercules Powder Company and DuPont Company, Atlas Powder Company also supported the Allied armies during World War II.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Employment at Atlas reached its greatest peak during this period, reaching 1,617 in 1947.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] This number declined with the decreasing use of anthracite.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Atlas Powder Company was renamed as Atlas Chemical Industries, which became a corporate predecessor of AstraZeneca, through an acquisition in 1971 by Imperial Chemical Industries.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] Another technology attributed to the company was the HLB number scale, which was considered the first ever successful attempt of a quantitative characterization of the hydrophile-lipophile balance of different surfactants.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] In collaboration with the University of Pittsburgh, it developed a stable polymorph of sorbitol during the 1960s.
[src:detonator/atlas-powder-company] In 1984, Atlas Powder Company filed a patent infringement case against DuPont over an invention that featured a water-resistant emulsion-based blasting agent.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Born in the Province of Massachusetts Bay, Franklin became a successful newspaper editor and printer in Philadelphia, the leading city in the colonies, publishing *The Pennsylvania Gazette* at age 23.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became wealthy publishing this and *Poor Richard's Almanack*, which he wrote under the pseudonym "Richard Saunders".
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After 1767, he was associated with the *Pennsylvania Chronicle*, a newspaper known for its revolutionary sentiments and criticisms of the policies of the British Parliament and the Crown.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He pioneered and was the first president of the Academy and College of Philadelphia, which opened in 1751 and later became the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He organized and was the first secretary of the American Philosophical Society and was elected its president in 1769.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was appointed deputy postmaster-general for the British colonies in 1753, which enabled him to set up the first national communications network.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was active in community affairs and colonial and state politics, as well as national and international affairs.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became a hero in North America when, as an agent in London for several colonies, he spearheaded the repeal of the unpopular Stamp Act by the British Parliament.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] An accomplished diplomat, he was widely admired as the first U.S. ambassador to France and was a major figure in the development of positive Franco–American relations.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His efforts proved vital in securing French aid for the American Revolution.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] From 1785 to 1788, he served as President of Pennsylvania.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] As a scientist, Franklin's studies of electricity made him a major figure in the American Enlightenment and the history of physics.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He also charted and named the Gulf Stream current.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His numerous important inventions include the lightning rod, bifocals, glass harmonica and the Franklin stove.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He founded many civic organizations, including the Library Company, the University of Pennsylvania, and Philadelphia's first fire department.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin earned the title of "The First American" for his early and indefatigable campaigning for colonial unity.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was the only person to sign the Declaration of Independence, the Treaty of Paris peace with Britain, and the Constitution.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Foundational in defining the American ethos, Franklin has been called "the most accomplished American of his age and the most influential in inventing the type of society America would become".
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His more than 30,000 letters and documents have been collected in *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Anne Robert Jacques Turgot said of him: "Eripuit fulmen cœlo, mox sceptra tyrannis" ("He snatched lightning from the sky and the scepter from tyrants").
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin's father, Josiah Franklin, was a tallow chandler, soaper, and candlemaker.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Josiah Franklin was born at Ecton, Northamptonshire, England, on December 23, 1657, to Thomas Franklin and Jane White.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin's father and all four of his grandparents were born in England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Josiah Franklin had a total of seventeen children with his two wives.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He married his first wife, Anne Child, in about 1677 in Ecton and emigrated with her to Boston in 1683; they had three children before emigration and four after.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Following her death, Josiah married Abiah Folger on July 9, 1689, in the Old South Meeting House by Reverend Samuel Willard, and had ten children with her.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin, their eighth child, was Josiah Franklin's fifteenth child overall, and his tenth and final son.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin's mother, Abiah, was born in Nantucket, Massachusetts Bay Colony, on August 15, 1667, to Peter Folger, a miller and schoolteacher, and his wife, Mary Morrell Folger, a former indentured servant.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Mary Folger came from a Puritan family that was among the first Pilgrims to flee to Massachusetts for religious freedom, sailing for Boston in 1635 after King Charles I of England had begun persecuting Puritans.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Her father Peter was "the sort of rebel destined to transform colonial America." As clerk of the court, he was arrested on February 10, 1676, and jailed on February 19 for his inability to pay bail.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He spent over a year and a half in jail.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was born on Milk Street in Boston, Province of Massachusetts Bay, on January 17, 1706, and baptized at the Old South Meeting House in Boston.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's father wanted him to attend school with the clergy but only had enough money to send him to school for two years.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He attended Boston Latin School but did not graduate; he continued his education through voracious reading.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although "his parents talked of the church as a career" for Franklin, his schooling ended when he was ten.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He worked for his father for a time, and at 12 he became an apprentice to his brother James, a printer, who taught him the printing trade.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When Benjamin was 15, James founded *The New-England Courant*, which was the third newspaper founded in Boston.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When denied the chance to write a letter to the paper for publication, Franklin adopted the pseudonym of "Silence Dogood", a middle-aged widow.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Dogood's letters were published and became a subject of conversation around town.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Neither James nor the *Courant*'s readers were aware of the ruse, and James was unhappy with Benjamin when he discovered the popular correspondent was his younger brother.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was an advocate of free speech from an early age.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When his brother was jailed for three weeks in 1722 for publishing material unflattering to the governor, young Franklin took over the newspaper and had Mrs.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Dogood proclaim, quoting *Cato's Letters*, "Without freedom of thought there can be no such thing as wisdom and no such thing as public liberty without freedom of speech." Franklin left his apprenticeship without his brother's permission, and in so doing became a fugitive.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At age 17, Franklin ran away to Philadelphia, seeking a new start in a new city.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he first arrived, he worked in several printing shops there, but he was not satisfied by the immediate prospects in any of these jobs.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After a few months, while Franklin was working in one printing house, Pennsylvania governor Sir William Keith convinced him to go to London, ostensibly to acquire the equipment necessary for establishing another newspaper in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Discovering that Keith's promises of backing a newspaper were empty, he worked as a typesetter in a printer's shop in what is today the Lady Chapel of Church of St Bartholomew-the-Great in the Smithfield area of London, which had at that time been deconsecrated.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He returned to Philadelphia in 1726 with the help of Thomas Denham, an English merchant who had emigrated but returned to England, and who employed Franklin as a clerk, shopkeeper, and bookkeeper in his business.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1727, at age 21, Franklin formed the Junto, a group of "like minded aspiring artisans and tradesmen who hoped to improve themselves while they improved their community." The Junto was a discussion group for issues of the day; it subsequently gave rise to many organizations in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Junto was modeled after English coffeehouses that Franklin knew well and which had become the center of the spread of Enlightenment ideas in Britain.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Reading was a great pastime of the Junto, but books were rare and expensive.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin conceived the idea of a subscription library, which would pool the funds of the members to buy books for all to read.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This was the birth of the Library Company of Philadelphia, whose charter he composed in 1731.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Upon Denham's death, Franklin returned to his former trade.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1728, he set up a printing house in partnership with Hugh Meredith; the following year he became the publisher of *The Pennsylvania Gazette*, a newspaper in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* gave Franklin a forum for agitation about a variety of local reforms and initiatives through printed essays and observations.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Over time, his commentary, and his adroit cultivation of a positive image as an industrious and intellectual young man, earned him a great deal of social respect.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] But even after he achieved fame as a scientist and statesman, he habitually signed his letters with the unpretentious 'B.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1732, he published the first German-language newspaper in America – *Die Philadelphische Zeitung* – although it failed after only one year because four other newly founded German papers quickly dominated the newspaper market.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also printed Moravian religious books in German.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He often visited Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, staying at the Moravian Sun Inn.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In a 1751 pamphlet on demographic growth and its implications for the Thirteen Colonies, he called the Pennsylvania Germans "Palatine Boors" who could never acquire the "Complexion" of Anglo-American settlers and referred to "Blacks and Tawneys" as weakening the social structure of the colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although he apparently reconsidered shortly thereafter, and the phrases were omitted from all later printings of the pamphlet, his views may have played a role in his political defeat in 1764.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] According to Ralph Frasca, Franklin promoted the printing press as a device to instruct colonial Americans in moral virtue.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Frasca argues he saw this as a service to God, because he understood moral virtue in terms of actions, thus, doing good provides a service to God.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Despite his own moral lapses, Franklin saw himself as uniquely qualified to instruct Americans in morality.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He tried to influence American moral life through the construction of a printing network based on a chain of partnerships from the Carolinas to New England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He thereby invented the first newspaper chain.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was more than a business venture, for like many publishers he believed that the press had a public-service duty.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he established himself in Philadelphia, shortly before 1730, the town boasted two "wretched little" news sheets, Andrew Bradford's *The American Weekly Mercury* and Samuel Keimer's *Universal Instructor in all Arts and Sciences, and Pennsylvania Gazette*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This instruction in all arts and sciences consisted of weekly extracts from *Chambers's Universal Dictionary*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin quickly did away with all of this when he took over the *Instructor* and made it *The Pennsylvania Gazette*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* soon became his characteristic organ, which he freely used for satire, for the play of his wit, even for sheer excess of mischief or of fun.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] From the first, he had a way of adapting his models to his own uses.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The series of essays called "The Busy-Body", which he wrote for Bradford's *American Mercury* in 1729, followed the general Addisonian form, already modified to suit homelier conditions.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The thrifty Patience, in her busy little shop, complaining of the useless visitors who waste her valuable time, is related to the women who address Mr.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Busy-Body himself is a true Censor Morum, as Isaac Bickerstaff had been in the *Tatler*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] And a number of the fictitious characters, Ridentius, Eugenius, Cato, and Cretico, represent traditional 18th-century classicism.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin even used this classical framework for contemporary satire, as seen in the character of Cretico, the "sour Philosopher", who is clearly a caricature of his rival, Samuel Keimer.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin had mixed success in his plan to establish an inter-colonial network of newspapers that would produce a profit for him and disseminate virtue.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Over the years he sponsored two dozen printers in Pennsylvania, South Carolina, New York, Connecticut, and even the Caribbean.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] By 1753, eight of the fifteen English language newspapers in the colonies were published by him or his partners.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He began in Charleston, South Carolina, in 1731.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his second editor died, the widow, Elizabeth Timothy, took over and made it a success.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] She was one of the colonial era's first woman printers.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] For three decades Franklin maintained a close business relationship with her and her son Peter Timothy, who took over the *South Carolina Gazette* in 1746.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* was impartial in political debates, while creating the opportunity for public debate, which encouraged others to challenge authority.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Timothy avoided blandness and crude bias and, after 1765, increasingly took a patriotic stand in the growing crisis with Great Britain.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's *Connecticut Gazette* (1755–68), however, proved unsuccessful.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] As the Revolution approached, political strife slowly tore his network apart.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1730 or 1731, Franklin was initiated into the local Masonic lodge.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became a grand master in 1734, indicating his rapid rise to prominence in Pennsylvania.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The same year, he edited and published the first Masonic book in the Americas, a reprint of James Anderson's *Constitutions of the Free-Masons*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] John's Lodge in Philadelphia from 1735 to 1738.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In January 1738, "Franklin appeared as a witness" in a manslaughter trial against two men who killed "a simple-minded apprentice" named Daniel Rees in a fake Masonic initiation gone wrong.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] One of the men "threw, or accidentally spilled, the burning spirits, and Daniel Rees died of his burns two days later." While Franklin did not directly participate in the hazing that led to Rees's death, he knew of the hazing before it turned fatal, and did nothing to stop it.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was criticized for his inaction in *The American Weekly Mercury*, by his publishing rival Andrew Bradford.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin remained a Freemason for the rest of his life.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At age 17 in 1723, Franklin proposed to 15-year-old Deborah Read while a boarder in the Read home.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At that time, Deborah's mother was wary of allowing her young daughter to marry Franklin, who was on his way to London at Governor Keith's request, and also because of his financial instability.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Her own husband had recently died, and she declined Franklin's request to marry her daughter.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin travelled to London, and after he failed to communicate as expected with Deborah and her family, they interpreted his long silence as a breaking of his promises.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At the urging of her mother, Deborah married a potter named John Rogers on August 5, 1725.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] John soon fled to Barbados with her dowry in order to avoid debts and prosecution.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Since Rogers's fate was unknown, bigamy laws prevented Deborah from remarrying.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin returned in 1726 and resumed his courtship of Deborah.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] They established a common-law marriage on September 1, 1730.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] They took in his recently acknowledged illegitimate young son and raised him in their household.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Their son, Francis Folger Franklin, was born in October 1732 and died of smallpox in 1736.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Their daughter, Sarah "Sally" Franklin, was born in 1743 and eventually married Richard Bache.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deborah wrote to him in November 1769, saying she was ill due to "dissatisfied distress" from his prolonged absence, but he did not return until his business was done.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deborah Read Franklin died of a stroke on December 14, 1774, while Franklin was on an extended mission to Great Britain; he returned in 1775.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1730, 24-year-old Franklin publicly acknowledged his illegitimate son William and raised him in his household.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] William was born on February 22, 1730, but his mother's identity is unknown.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was educated in Philadelphia and beginning at about age 30 studied law in London in the early 1760s.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] William himself fathered an illegitimate son, William Temple Franklin, born on the same day and month: February 22, 1760.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The boy's mother was never identified, and he was placed in foster care.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1762, the elder William Franklin married Elizabeth Downes, daughter of a planter from Barbados, in London.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1763, he was appointed as the last royal governor of New Jersey.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] A Loyalist to the king, William Franklin saw his relations with father Benjamin eventually break down over their differences about the American Revolutionary War, as Benjamin Franklin could never accept William's position.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deposed in 1776 by the revolutionary government of New Jersey, William was placed under house arrest at his home in Perth Amboy for six months.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When finally released in a prisoner exchange in 1778, he moved to New York City, which was occupied by the British at the time.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] While in New York City, he became leader of the Board of Associated Loyalists, a quasi-military organization chartered by King George III and headquartered in New York City.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] They initiated guerrilla forays into New Jersey, southern Connecticut, and New York counties north of the city.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When British troops evacuated from New York, William Franklin left with them and sailed to England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He settled in London, never to return to North America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In the preliminary peace talks in 1782 with Britain, "...
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin insisted that loyalists who had borne arms against the United States would be excluded from this plea (that they be given a general pardon).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1732, Franklin began to publish the noted *Poor Richard's Almanack* (with content both original and borrowed) under the pseudonym Richard Saunders, on which much of his popular reputation is based.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The first issue published was for the upcoming year, 1733.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had developed a distinct, signature style that was plain, pragmatic and had a sly, soft but self-deprecating tone with declarative sentences.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although it was no secret that he was the author, his Richard Saunders character repeatedly denied it.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] "Poor Richard's Proverbs", adages from this almanac, such as "A penny saved is twopence dear" (often misquoted as "A penny saved is a penny earned") and "Fish and visitors stink in three days", remain common quotations in the modern world.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Wisdom in folk society meant the ability to provide an apt adage for any occasion, and his readers became well prepared.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He sold about ten thousand copies per year—it became an institution.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1741, Franklin began publishing *The General Magazine and Historical Chronicle for all the British Plantations in America*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He used the heraldic badge of the Prince of Wales as the cover illustration.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin wrote a letter, "Advice to a Friend on Choosing a Mistress", dated June 25, 1745, in which he gives advice to a young man about channeling sexual urges.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Due to its licentious nature, it was not published in collections of his papers during the 19th century.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Federal court rulings from the mid-to-late 20th century cited the document as a reason for overturning obscenity laws and against censorship.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1736, Franklin created the Union Fire Company, one of the first volunteer firefighting companies in America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In the same year, he printed a new currency for New Jersey based on innovative anti-counterfeiting techniques he had devised.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His political career also commenced, particularly as the Chief Clerk of the Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly, a capacity wherein he served until 1751.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Throughout his career, he was an advocate for paper money, publishing *A Modest Enquiry into the Nature and Necessity of a Paper Currency* in 1729, and his printer printed money.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was influential in the more restrained and thus successful monetary experiments in the Middle Colonies, which stopped deflation without causing excessive inflation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1766, he made a case for paper money to the British House of Commons.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] As he matured, Franklin began to concern himself more with public affairs.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1743, he first devised a scheme for the Academy, Charity School, and College of Philadelphia; however, the person he had in mind to run the academy, Rev.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Richard Peters, refused and Franklin put his ideas away until 1749 when he printed his own pamphlet, *Proposals Relating to the Education of Youth in Pensilvania*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was appointed president of the Academy on November 13, 1749; the academy and the charity school opened in 1751.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1743, he founded the American Philosophical Society to help scientific men discuss their discoveries and theories.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He began the electrical research that, along with other scientific inquiries, would occupy him for the rest of his life, in between bouts of politics and moneymaking.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The largest of these was the "Association Battery" or "Grand Battery" of 50 guns.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1747, Franklin (already a very wealthy man) retired from printing and went into other businesses.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He formed a partnership with his foreman, David Hall, which provided Franklin with half of the shop's profits for 18 years.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This lucrative business arrangement provided leisure time for study, and in a few years he had made many new discoveries.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became involved in Philadelphia politics and rapidly progressed.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In October 1748, he was selected as a councilman; in June 1749, he became a justice of the peace for Philadelphia; and in 1751, he was elected to the Pennsylvania Assembly.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On August 10, 1753, he was appointed deputy postmaster-general of British North America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His service in domestic politics included reforming the postal system, with mail sent out every week.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1751, Franklin and Thomas Bond obtained a charter from the Pennsylvania legislature to establish a hospital.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Pennsylvania Hospital was the first hospital in the colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1752, Franklin organized the Philadelphia Contributionship, the Colonies' first homeowner's insurance company.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin solicited, printed in 1752, and promoted an American textbook of moral philosophy by Samuel Johnson, titled *Elementa Philosophica*, to be taught in the new colleges.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In June 1753, Johnson, Franklin, and Smith met in Stratford.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] They decided the new-model college would focus on the professions, with classes taught in English instead of Latin, have subject matter experts as professors instead of one tutor leading a class for four years, and there would be no religious test for admission.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Johnson went on to found King's College (now Columbia University) in New York City in 1754, while Franklin hired Smith as provost of the College of Philadelphia, which opened in 1755.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At its first commencement, on May 17, 1757, seven men graduated; six with a Bachelor of Arts and one with a Master of Arts.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was later merged with the University of the State of Pennsylvania to become the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1754, he headed the Pennsylvania delegation to the Albany Congress.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This meeting of several colonies had been requested by the Board of Trade in England to improve relations with the Indians and defense against the French.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin proposed a broad Plan of Union for the colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] While the plan was not adopted, elements of it found their way into the Articles of Confederation and the Constitution.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1753, Harvard University and Yale awarded him honorary master of arts degrees.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1756, he was awarded an honorary Master of Arts degree from the College of William & Mary.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Later in 1756, Franklin organized the Pennsylvania Militia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He used Tun Tavern as a gathering place to recruit a regiment of soldiers to go into battle against the Native American uprisings that beset the American colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Well known as a printer and publisher, Franklin was appointed postmaster of Philadelphia in 1737, holding the office until 1753, when he and publisher William Hunter were named deputy postmasters–general of British North America, the first to hold the office.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] (Joint appointments were standard at the time, for political reasons.) He was responsible for the British colonies from Pennsylvania north and east, as far as the island of Newfoundland.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] A post office for local and outgoing mail had been established in Halifax, Nova Scotia, by local stationer Benjamin Leigh, on April 23, 1754, but service was irregular.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin opened the first post office to offer regular, monthly mail in Halifax on December 9, 1755.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Meantime, Hunter became postal administrator in Williamsburg, Virginia, and oversaw areas south of Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin reorganized the service's accounting system and improved speed of delivery between Philadelphia, New York, and Boston.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] By 1761, efficiencies led to the first profits for the colonial post office.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When the lands of New France were ceded to the British under the Treaty of Paris in 1763, the British province of Quebec was created among them, and Franklin saw mail service expanded between Montreal, Trois-Rivières, Quebec City, and New York.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] For the greater part of his appointment, he lived in England (from 1757 to 1762, and again from 1764 to 1774)—about three-quarters of his term.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Eventually, his sympathies for the rebel cause in the American Revolution led to his dismissal on January 31, 1774.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On July 26, 1775, the Second Continental Congress established the United States Post Office and named Franklin as the first United States postmaster general.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had been a postmaster for decades and was a natural choice for the position.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had just returned from England and was appointed chairman of a Committee of Investigation to establish a postal system.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The report of the committee, providing for the appointment of a postmaster general for the 13 American colonies, was considered by the Continental Congress on July 25 and 26.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On July 26, 1775, Franklin was appointed postmaster general, the first appointed under the Continental Congress.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His apprentice, William Goddard, felt that his ideas were mostly responsible for shaping the postal system and that the appointment should have gone to him, but he graciously conceded it to Franklin, 36 years his senior.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin, however, appointed Goddard as Surveyor of the Posts, issued him a signed pass, and directed him to investigate and inspect the various post offices and mail routes as he saw fit.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The newly established postal system became the United States Post Office, a system that continues to operate today.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1757, he was sent to England by the Pennsylvania Assembly as a colonial agent to protest against the political influence of the Penn family, the proprietors of the colony.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He remained there for five years, striving to end the proprietors' prerogative to overturn legislation from the elected Assembly and their exemption from paying taxes on their land.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His lack of influential allies in Whitehall led to the failure of this mission.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] At this time, many members of the Pennsylvania Assembly were feuding with William Penn's heirs, who controlled the colony as proprietors.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return to the colony, Franklin led the "anti-proprietary party" in the struggle against the Penn family and was elected Speaker of the Pennsylvania House in May 1764.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His call for a change from proprietary to royal government was a rare political miscalculation, however: Pennsylvanians worried that such a move would endanger their political and religious freedoms.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Because of these fears and because of political attacks on his character, Franklin lost his seat in the October 1764 Assembly elections.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The anti-proprietary party dispatched him to England again to continue the struggle against the Penn family proprietorship.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] During this trip, events drastically changed the nature of his mission.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In London, Franklin opposed the 1765 Stamp Act.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Unable to prevent its passage, he made another political miscalculation and recommended a friend, John Hughes, to the post of stamp distributor for Pennsylvania.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Pennsylvanians were outraged, believing that he had supported the measure all along, and threatened to destroy his home in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin soon learned of the extent of colonial resistance to the Stamp Act, and he testified during the House of Commons proceedings that led to its repeal.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] With this, Franklin suddenly emerged as the leading spokesman for American interests in England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He wrote popular essays on behalf of the colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Georgia, New Jersey, and Massachusetts also appointed him as their agent to the Crown.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his lengthy missions to London between 1757 and 1775, Franklin lodged in a house on Craven Street, just off the Strand in central London.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his stays there, he developed a close friendship with his landlady, Margaret Stevenson, and her circle of friends and relations, in particular, her daughter Mary, who was more often known as Polly.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The house is now a museum known as the Benjamin Franklin House.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Whilst in London, Franklin became involved in radical politics.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He belonged to a gentlemen's club (which he called "the honest Whigs"), which held stated meetings, and included members such as Richard Price, the minister of Newington Green Unitarian Church who ignited the Revolution controversy, and Andrew Kippis.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1756, Franklin had become a member of the Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures & Commerce (now the Royal Society of Arts), which had been founded in 1754.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return to the United States in 1775, he became the Society's Corresponding Member, continuing a close connection.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Royal Society of Arts instituted a Benjamin Franklin Medal in 1956 to commemorate the 250th anniversary of his birth and the 200th anniversary of his membership of the RSA.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The study of natural philosophy (referred today as science in general) drew him into overlapping circles of acquaintance.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was, for example, a corresponding member of the Lunar Society of Birmingham.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1759, the University of St Andrews awarded him an honorary doctorate in recognition of his accomplishments.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In October 1759, he was granted Freedom of the Borough of St Andrews.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was also awarded an honorary doctorate by Oxford University in 1762.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Because of these honors, he was often addressed as "Dr.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] While living in London in 1768, he developed a phonetic alphabet in *A Scheme for a new Alphabet and a Reformed Mode of Spelling*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This reformed alphabet discarded six letters he regarded as redundant (c, j, q, w, x, and y), and substituted six new letters for sounds he felt lacked letters of their own.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This alphabet never caught on, and he eventually lost interest.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] From the mid-1750s to the mid-1770s, Franklin returned to England and spent much of his time in London., using the city as a base from which to travel.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1771, he made short journeys through different parts of England, staying with Joseph Priestley at Leeds, Thomas Percival at Manchester and Erasmus Darwin at Lichfield.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In Scotland, he spent five days with Lord Kames near Stirling and stayed for three weeks with David Hume in Edinburgh.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In Ireland, he stayed with Lord Hillsborough.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was the first American to receive this honor.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] While touring Ireland, he was deeply moved by the level of poverty he witnessed.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The economy of the Kingdom of Ireland was affected by the same trade regulations and laws that governed the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin spent two months in German lands in 1766, but his connections to the country stretched across a lifetime.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He declared a debt of gratitude to German scientist Otto von Guericke for his early studies of electricity.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also co-authored the first treaty of friendship between Prussia and America in 1785.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In September 1767, he visited Paris with his usual traveling partner, Sir John Pringle, 1st Baronet.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] News of his electrical discoveries was widespread in France.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His reputation meant that he was introduced to many influential scientists and politicians, and also to King Louis XV.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] One line of argument in Parliament was that Americans should pay a share of the costs of the French and Indian War and therefore taxes should be levied on them.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became the American spokesman in highly publicized testimony in Parliament in 1766.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He stated that Americans already contributed heavily to the defense of the Empire.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He said local governments had raised, outfitted and paid 25,000 soldiers to fight France—as many as Great Britain itself sent—and spent many millions from American treasuries doing so in the French and Indian War alone.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1772, Franklin obtained private letters of Thomas Hutchinson and Andrew Oliver, governor and lieutenant governor of the Province of Massachusetts Bay, proving that they had encouraged the Crown to crack down on Bostonians.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin sent them to North America, where they escalated tensions.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The letters were finally leaked to the public in the *Boston Gazette* in mid-June 1773, causing a political firestorm in Massachusetts and raising significant questions in England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The British began to regard him as the fomenter of serious trouble.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Hopes for a peaceful solution ended as he was systematically ridiculed and humiliated by Solicitor-General Alexander Wedderburn, before the Privy Council on January 29, 1774.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He returned to Philadelphia in March 1775, and abandoned his accommodationist stance.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin is known to have occasionally attended the Hellfire Club's meetings during 1758 as a non-member during his time in England.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] However, some authors and historians would argue he was in fact a British spy.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] As there are no records left (having been burned in 1774), many of these members are just assumed or linked by letters sent to each other.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] One early proponent that Franklin was a member of the Hellfire Club and a double agent is the historian Donald McCormick, who has a history of making controversial claims.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1763, soon after Franklin returned to Pennsylvania from England for the first time, the western frontier was engulfed in a bitter war known as Pontiac's Rebellion.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Paxton Boys, a group of settlers convinced that the Pennsylvania government was not doing enough to protect them from American Indian raids, murdered a group of peaceful Susquehannock Indians and marched on Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin helped to organize a local militia to defend the capital against the mob.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He met with the Paxton leaders and persuaded them to disperse.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin wrote a scathing attack against the racial prejudice of the Paxton Boys.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He provided an early response to British surveillance through his own network of counter-surveillance and manipulation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] By the time Franklin arrived in Philadelphia on May 5, 1775, after his second mission to Great Britain, the American Revolution had begun at the Battles of Lexington and Concord the previous month, on April 19, 1775.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The New England militia had forced the main British army to remain inside Boston.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Pennsylvania Assembly unanimously chose Franklin as their delegate to the Second Continental Congress.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In June 1776, he was appointed a member of the Committee of Five that drafted the Declaration of Independence.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although he was temporarily disabled by gout and unable to attend most meetings of the committee, he made several "small but important" changes to the draft sent to him by Thomas Jefferson.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The "all hang together" saying ascribed to Franklin at the signing is probably apocryphal.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On October 26, 1776, Franklin was dispatched to France as commissioner for the United States.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He took with him as secretary his 16-year-old grandson, William Temple Franklin.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] They lived in a home in the Parisian suburb of Passy, donated by Jacques-Donatien Le Ray de Chaumont, who supported the United States.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Among his associates in France was Honoré Gabriel Riqueti, comte de Mirabeau—a French Revolutionary writer, orator and statesman who in 1791 was elected president of the National Assembly.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In July 1784, Franklin met with Mirabeau and contributed anonymous materials that the Frenchman used in his first signed work: *Considerations sur l'ordre de Cincinnatus*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The publication was critical of the Society of the Cincinnati, established in the United States.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin and Mirabeau thought of it as a "noble order", inconsistent with the egalitarian ideals of the new republic.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his stay in France, he was active as a Freemason, serving as venerable master of the lodge Les Neuf Sœurs from 1779 until 1781.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1784, when Franz Mesmer began to publicize his theory of "animal magnetism" which was considered offensive by many, Louis XVI appointed a commission to investigate it.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] These included the chemist Antoine Lavoisier, the physician Joseph-Ignace Guillotin, the astronomer Jean Sylvain Bailly, and Franklin.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's advocacy for religious tolerance in France contributed to arguments made by French philosophers and politicians that resulted in Louis XVI's signing of the Edict of Versailles in November 1787.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] This edict effectively nullified the Edict of Fontainebleau, which had denied non-Catholics civil status and the right to openly practice their faith.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also served as American minister to Sweden, although he never visited that country.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He negotiated a treaty that was signed in April 1783.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On August 27, 1783, in Paris, he witnessed the world's first hydrogen balloon flight.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] *Le Globe*, created by professor Jacques Charles and Les Frères Robert, was watched by a vast crowd as it rose from the Champ de Mars (now the site of the Eiffel Tower).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became so enthusiastic that he subscribed financially to the next project to build a manned hydrogen balloon.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] On December 1, 1783, Franklin was seated in the special enclosure for honored guests it took off from the Jardin des Tuileries, piloted by Charles and Nicolas-Louis Robert.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Walter Isaacson describes a chess game between Franklin and the Duchess of Bourbon, "who made a move that inadvertently exposed her king.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Ignoring the rules of the game, he promptly captured it.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he returned home in 1785, Franklin occupied a position second only to that of George Washington as the champion of American independence.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Le Ray honored him with a commissioned portrait painted by Joseph Duplessis, which now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery of the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, D.C.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return, Franklin became an abolitionist and freed his two slaves.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He eventually became president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Special balloting conducted October 18, 1785, unanimously elected him the sixth president of the Supreme Executive Council of Pennsylvania, replacing John Dickinson.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] The office was practically that of the governor.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He held that office for slightly over three years, longer than any other, and served the constitutional limit of three full terms.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Shortly after his initial election, he was re-elected to a full term on October 29, 1785, and again in the fall of 1786 and on October 31, 1787.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In that capacity, he served as host to the Constitutional Convention of 1787 in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] He also served as a delegate to the Convention.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was primarily an honorary position and he seldom engaged in debate.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] According to James McHenry, Elizabeth Willing Powel asked Franklin what kind of government they had wrought.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin suffered from obesity throughout his middle age and elder years, which resulted in multiple health problems, including gout, which worsened as he aged.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] In poor health during the signing of the U.S.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Constitution in 1787, he was rarely seen in public after then until his death.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin died from pleuritic attack at his home in Philadelphia on April 17, 1790, at age 84.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] His last reported words, conveyed to his daughter, were, "a dying man can do nothing easy", after she suggested that he change position in bed and lie on his side so he could breathe more easily.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Approximately 20,000 people attended Franklin's funeral, after which he was interred in Christ Church Burial Ground in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p01] Upon learning of his death, the Constitutional Assembly in Revolutionary France entered into a state of mourning for a period of three days, and memorial services were conducted in honor of Franklin throughout the country.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Among his many creations were the lightning rod, Franklin stove, bifocal glasses and the flexible urinary catheter.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was, along with his contemporary Leonhard Euler, the only major scientist who supported Christiaan Huygens's wave theory of light, which was basically ignored by the rest of the scientific community.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In the 18th century, Isaac Newton's corpuscular theory was held to be true; it took Thomas Young's well-known slit experiment in 1803 to persuade most scientists to believe Huygens's theory.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin started exploring the phenomenon of electricity in the 1740s, after he met the itinerant lecturer Archibald Spencer, who used static electricity in his demonstrations.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He proposed that "vitreous" and "resinous" electricity were not different types of "electrical fluid" (as electricity was called then), but the same "fluid" under different pressures.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1748, he constructed a multiple plate capacitor, that he called an "electrical battery" (not a true battery like Volta's pile) by placing eleven panes of glass sandwiched between lead plates, suspended with silk cords and connected by wires.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In pursuit of more pragmatic uses for electricity, remarking in spring 1749 that he felt "chagrin'd a little" that his experiments had heretofore resulted in "Nothing in this Way of Use to Mankind", Franklin planned a practical demonstration.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He proposed a dinner party where a turkey was to be killed via electric shock and roasted on an electrical spit.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin briefly investigated electrotherapy, including the use of the electric bath.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] This work led to the field becoming widely known.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In recognition of his work with electricity, he received the Royal Society's Copley Medal in 1753, and in 1756, he became one of the few 18th-century Americans elected a fellow of the Society.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The CGS unit of electric charge has been named after him: one *franklin* (Fr) is equal to one statcoulomb.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin advised Harvard University in its acquisition of new electrical laboratory apparatus after the complete loss of its original collection, in a fire that destroyed the original Harvard Hall in 1764.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The collection he assembled later became part of the Harvard Collection of Historical Scientific Instruments, now on public display in its Science Center.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin published a proposal for an experiment to prove that lightning is electricity by flying a kite in a storm.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] On May 10, 1752, Thomas-François Dalibard of France conducted Franklin's experiment using a 40-foot-tall (12 m) iron rod instead of a kite, and he extracted electrical sparks from a cloud.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] On June 15, 1752, Franklin may possibly have conducted his well-known kite experiment in Philadelphia, successfully extracting sparks from a cloud.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He described the experiment in his newspaper, *The Pennsylvania Gazette*, on October 19, 1752, without mentioning that he himself had performed it.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] This account was read to the Royal Society on December 21 and printed as such in the *Philosophical Transactions*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Joseph Priestley published an account with additional details in his 1767 *History and Present Status of Electricity*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was careful to stand on an insulator, keeping dry under a roof to avoid the danger of electric shock.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Others, such as Georg Wilhelm Richmann in Russia, were indeed electrocuted in performing lightning experiments during the months immediately following his experiment.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his writings, Franklin indicates that he was aware of the dangers and offered alternative ways to demonstrate that lightning was electrical, as shown by his use of the concept of electrical ground.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He did not perform this experiment in the way that is often pictured in popular literature, flying the kite and waiting to be struck by lightning, as it would have been dangerous.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Instead he used the kite to collect some electric charge from a storm cloud, showing that lightning was electrical.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's electrical experiments led to his invention of the lightning rod.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Though Franklin is famously associated with kites from his lightning experiments, he has also been noted by many for using kites to pull humans and ships across waterways.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] George Pocock in the book *A Treatise on The Aeropleustic Art, or Navigation in the Air, by means of Kites, or Buoyant Sails* noted being inspired by Benjamin Franklin's traction of his body by kite power across a waterway.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin noted a principle of refrigeration by observing that on a very hot day, he stayed cooler in a wet shirt in a breeze than he did in a dry one.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] To understand this phenomenon more clearly, he conducted experiments.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1758 on a warm day in Cambridge, England, he and fellow scientist John Hadley experimented by continually wetting the ball of a mercury thermometer with ether and using bellows to evaporate the ether.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] With each subsequent evaporation, the thermometer read a lower temperature, eventually reaching 7 °F (−14 °C).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Another thermometer showed that the room temperature was constant at 65 °F (18 °C).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1761, Franklin wrote a letter to Mary Stevenson describing his experiments on the relationship between color and heat absorption.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He found that darker color clothes got hotter when exposed to sunlight than lighter color clothes, an early demonstration of black body thermal radiation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] One experiment he performed consisted of placing square pieces of cloth of various color out in the snow on a sunny day.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He waited some time and then measured that the black pieces sank furthest into the snow of all the colors, indicating that they got the hottest and melted the most snow.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] According to Michael Faraday, Franklin's experiments on the non-conduction of ice are worth mentioning, although the law of the general effect of liquefaction on electrolytes is not attributed to Franklin.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, as reported in 1836 by Franklin's great-grandson Alexander Dallas Bache of the University of Pennsylvania, the law of the effect of heat on the conduction of bodies otherwise non-conductors, for example, glass, could be attributed to Franklin.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] A certain quantity of heat will make some bodies good conductors, that will not otherwise conduct ..." and again, "...
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] As deputy postmaster, Franklin became interested in North Atlantic Ocean circulation patterns.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] While in England in 1768, he heard a complaint from the Colonial Board of Customs.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] British packet ships carrying mail had taken several weeks longer to reach New York than it took an average merchant ship to reach Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The merchantmen had a longer and more complex voyage because they left from London, while the packets left from Falmouth in Cornwall.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin put the question to his cousin Timothy Folger, a Nantucket whaler captain, who told him that merchant ships routinely avoided a strong eastbound mid-ocean current.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The mail packet captains sailed dead into it, thus fighting an adverse current of 3 miles per hour (5 km/h).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin worked with Folger and other experienced ship captains, learning enough to chart the current and name it the Gulf Stream, by which it is still known today.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin published his Gulf Stream chart in 1770 in England, where it was ignored.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Subsequent versions were printed in France in 1778 and the U.S. in 1786.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The British original edition of the chart had been so thoroughly ignored that everyone assumed it was lost forever until Phil Richardson, a Woods Hole oceanographer and Gulf Stream expert, discovered it in the Bibliothèque Nationale in Paris in 1980.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] This find received front-page coverage in *The New York Times*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] It took many years for British sea captains to adopt Franklin's advice on navigating the current; once they did, they were able to trim two weeks from their sailing time.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] An aging Franklin accumulated all his oceanographic findings in *Maritime Observations*, published by the Philosophical Society's *transactions* in 1786.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] It contained ideas for sea anchors, catamaran hulls, watertight compartments, shipboard lightning rods and a soup bowl designed to stay stable in stormy weather.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] While traveling on a ship, Franklin had observed that the wake of a ship was diminished when the cooks scuttled their greasy water.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He studied the effects on a large pond in Clapham Common, London.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] On October 21, 1743, according to the popular myth, a storm moving from the southwest denied Franklin the opportunity of witnessing a lunar eclipse.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was said to have noted that the prevailing winds were actually from the northeast, contrary to what he had expected.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In correspondence with his brother, he learned that the same storm had not reached Boston until after the eclipse, despite the fact that Boston is to the northeast of Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He deduced that storms do not always travel in the direction of the prevailing wind, a concept that greatly influenced meteorology.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] After the Icelandic volcanic eruption of Laki in 1783, and the subsequent harsh European winter of 1784, Franklin made observations on the causal nature of these two seemingly separate events.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He wrote about them in a lecture series.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin had a major influence on the emerging science of demography or population studies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In the 1730s and 1740s, he began taking notes on population growth, finding that the American population had the fastest growth rate on Earth.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Emphasizing that population growth depended on food supplies, he emphasized the abundance of food and available farmland in America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He calculated that America's population was doubling every 20 years and would surpass that of England in a century.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's predictions on how British mercantilism was unsustainable alarmed British leaders who did not want to be surpassed by the colonies, so they became more willing to impose restrictions on the colonial economy.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his capacity as a farmer, he wrote at least one critique about the negative consequences of price controls, trade restrictions, and subsidy of the poor.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Like the other advocates of republicanism, Franklin emphasized that the new republic could survive only if the people were virtuous.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] All his life, he explored the role of civic and personal virtue, as expressed in *Poor Richard's* aphorisms.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He felt that organized religion was necessary to keep men good to their fellow men, but rarely attended religious services himself.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's parents were both pious Puritans.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The family attended the Old South Church, the most liberal Puritan congregation in Boston, where Benjamin Franklin was baptized in 1706.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's father, a poor chandler, owned a copy of a book, *Bonifacius: Essays to Do Good*, by the Puritan preacher and family friend Cotton Mather, which Franklin often cited as a key influence on his life.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] "If I have been a useful citizen," Franklin wrote to Cotton Mather's son seventy years later, "the public owes the advantage of it to that book." His first pen name, Silence Dogood, paid homage both to the book and to a widely known sermon by Mather.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The book preached the importance of forming voluntary associations to benefit society.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin learned about forming do-good associations from Mather, but his organizational skills made him the most influential force in making voluntarism an enduring part of the American ethos.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin formulated a presentation of his beliefs and published it in 1728.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He no longer accepted the key Puritan ideas regarding salvation, the divinity of Jesus, or indeed much religious dogma.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He classified himself as a deist in his 1771 autobiography, although he still considered himself a Christian.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He retained a strong faith in a God as the wellspring of morality and goodness in man, and as a Providential actor in history responsible for American independence.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The motion gained almost no support and was never brought to a vote.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was an enthusiastic admirer of the evangelical minister George Whitefield during the First Great Awakening.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He did not himself subscribe to Whitefield's theology, but he admired Whitefield for exhorting people to worship God through good works.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He published all of Whitefield's sermons and journals, thereby earning a lot of money and boosting the Great Awakening.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin retained a lifelong commitment to the non-religious Puritan virtues and political values he had grown up with, and through his civic work and publishing, he succeeded in passing these values into the American culture permanently.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He had a "passion for virtue." These Puritan values included his devotion to egalitarianism, education, industry, thrift, honesty, temperance, charity and community spirit.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The classical authors read in the Enlightenment period taught an abstract ideal of republican government based on hierarchical social orders of king, aristocracy and commoners.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] It was widely believed that English liberties relied on their balance of power, but also hierarchal deference to the privileged class.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin, steeped in Puritanism and an enthusiastic supporter of the evangelical movement, rejected the salvation dogma but embraced the radical notion of egalitarian democracy.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Max Weber considered Franklin's ethical writings a culmination of the Protestant ethic, which ethic created the social conditions necessary for the birth of capitalism.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] One of his characteristics was his respect, tolerance and promotion of all churches.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Ralph Frasca contends that in his later life he can be considered a non-denominational Christian, although he did not believe Christ was divine.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In a major scholarly study of his religion, Thomas Kidd argues that Franklin believed that true religiosity was a matter of personal morality and civic virtue.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Church of England claimed him as one of them.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] On July 4, 1776, Congress appointed a three-member committee composed of Franklin, Jefferson, and Adams to design the Great Seal of the United States.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's proposal (which was not adopted) featured the motto: "Rebellion to Tyrants is Obedience to God" and a scene from the Book of Exodus he took from the frontispiece of the Geneva Bible, with Moses, the Israelites, the pillar of fire, and George III depicted as pharaoh.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The design that was produced was not acted upon by Congress, and the Great Seal's design was not finalized until a third committee was appointed in 1782.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin sought to cultivate his character by a plan of 13 virtues, which he developed at age 20 (in 1726) and continued to practice in some form for the rest of his life.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Speak not but what may benefit others or yourself; avoid trifling conversation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Let all your things have their places; let each part of your business have its time.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Resolve to perform what you ought; perform without fail what you resolve.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Make no expense but to do good to others or yourself; i.e., waste nothing.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Lose no time; be always employ'd in something useful; cut off all unnecessary actions.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Use no hurtful deceit; think innocently and justly, and, if you speak, speak accordingly.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Wrong none by doing injuries, or omitting the benefits that are your duty.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Avoid extremes; forbear resenting injuries so much as you think they deserve.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Tolerate no uncleanliness in body, clothes, or habitation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Be not disturbed at trifles, or at accidents common or unavoidable.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Rarely use venery but for health or offspring, never to dullness, weakness, or the injury of your own or another's peace or reputation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin did not try to work on them all at once.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's views and practices concerning slavery evolved over the course of his life.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his early years, Franklin owned seven slaves, including two men who worked in his household and his shop, but in his later years became an adherent of abolition.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] A revenue stream for his newspaper was paid ads for the sale of slaves and for the capture of runaway slaves and Franklin allowed the sale of slaves in his general store.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He later became an outspoken critic of slavery.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1758, he advocated the opening of a school for the education of black slaves in Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He took two slaves to England with him, Peter and King.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] King escaped with a woman to live in the outskirts of London, and by 1758 he was working for a household in Suffolk.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] After returning from England in 1762, Franklin became more abolitionist in nature, attacking American slavery.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin refused to publicly debate the issue of slavery at the 1787 Constitutional Convention.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] At the time of the American founding, there were about half a million slaves in the United States, mostly in the five southernmost states, where they made up 40% of the population.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Many of the leading American founders – such as Thomas Jefferson, George Washington, and James Madison – owned slaves, but many others did not.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1790, Quakers from New York and Pennsylvania presented their petition for abolition to Congress.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Their argument against slavery was backed by the Pennsylvania Abolitionist Society.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his later years, as Congress was forced to deal with the issue of slavery, Franklin wrote several essays that stressed the importance of the abolition of slavery and of the integration of African Americans into American society.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin became a vegetarian when he was a teenager apprenticing at a print shop, after coming upon a book by the early vegetarian advocate Thomas Tryon.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In addition, he would have also been familiar with the moral arguments espoused by prominent vegetarian Quakers in the colonial-era Province of Pennsylvania, including Benjamin Lay and John Woolman.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin also declared the consumption of fish to be "unprovoked murder." Despite his convictions, he began to eat fish after being tempted by fried cod on a boat sailing from Boston, justifying the eating of animals by observing that the fish's stomach contained other fish.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Nonetheless, he recognized the faulty ethics in this argument and would continue to be a vegetarian on and off.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was "excited" by tofu, which he learned of from the writings of a Spanish missionary to Southeast Asia, Domingo Fernández Navarrete.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's "Second Reply to *Vindex Patriae,*" a 1766 letter advocating self-sufficiency and less dependence on England, lists various examples of the bounty of American agricultural products, and does not mention meat.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The concept of preventing smallpox by variolation was introduced to colonial America by an African slave named Onesimus via his owner Cotton Mather in the early eighteenth century, but the procedure was not immediately accepted.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] James Franklin's newspaper carried articles in 1721 that vigorously denounced the concept.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, by 1736 Benjamin Franklin was known as a supporter of the procedure.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Therefore, when four-year-old "Franky" died of smallpox, opponents of the procedure circulated rumors that the child had been inoculated, and that this was the cause of his subsequent death.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] When Franklin became aware of this gossip, he placed a notice in the *Pennsylvania Gazette*, stating: "I do hereby sincerely declare, that he was not inoculated, but receiv'd the Distemper in the common Way of Infection ...
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] I intended to have my Child inoculated." The child had a bad case of flux diarrhea, and his parents had waited for him to get well before having him inoculated.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin wrote in his *Autobiography*: "In 1736 I lost one of my sons, a fine boy of four years old, by the small-pox, taken in the common way.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] I long regretted bitterly, and still regret that I had not given it to him by inoculation.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In a letter to Joseph Priestley, dated February 8, 1780, Franklin speculated that in the future "all Diseases may by sure means be prevented or cured, not excepting even that of Old Age, and our Lives lengthened at pleasure even beyond the antediluvian Standard".
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin is known to have played the violin, the harp, and the guitar.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He also composed music, which included a string quartet in early classical style.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] While he was in London, he developed a much-improved version of the glass harmonica, in which the glasses rotate on a shaft, with the player's fingers held steady, instead of the other way around.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He worked with the London glassblower Charles James to create it, and instruments based on his mechanical version soon found their way to other parts of Europe.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Joseph Haydn, a fan of Franklin's enlightened ideas, had a glass harmonica in his instrument collection.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart composed for Franklin's glass harmonica, as did Ludwig van Beethoven.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Gaetano Donizetti used the instrument in the accompaniment to Amelia's aria "Par che mi dica ancora" in the tragic opera *Il castello di Kenilworth* (1821), as did Camille Saint-Saëns in his 1886 *The Carnival of the Animals*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Richard Strauss calls for the glass harmonica in his 1917 *Die Frau ohne Schatten*, and numerous other composers used Franklin's instrument as well.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was playing chess by around 1733, making him the first chess player known by name in the American colonies.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] His essay on "The Morals of Chess" in *Columbian Magazine* in December 1786 is the second known writing on chess in America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] This essay in praise of chess and prescribing a code of behavior for the game has been widely reprinted and translated.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He and a friend used chess as a means of learning the Italian language, which both were studying; the winner of each game between them had the right to assign a task, such as parts of the Italian grammar to be learned by heart, to be performed by the loser before their next meeting.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was able to play chess more frequently against stronger opposition during his many years as a civil servant and diplomat in England, where the game was far better established than in America.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was able to improve his playing standard by facing more experienced players during this period.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He regularly attended Old Slaughter's Coffee House in London for chess and socializing, making many important personal contacts.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] While in Paris, both as a visitor and later as ambassador, he visited the famous Café de la Régence, which France's strongest players made their regular meeting place.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] No records of his games have survived, so it is not possible to ascertain his playing strength in modern terms.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Franklin Mercantile Chess Club in Philadelphia, the second oldest chess club in the U.S., is named in his honor.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin bequeathed £1,000 (about $4,400 at the time, or about $125,000 in 2021 dollars) each to the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, in trust to gather interest for 200 years.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The trust began in 1785 when the French mathematician Charles-Joseph Mathon de la Cour, who admired Franklin greatly, wrote a friendly parody of Franklin's *Poor Richard's Almanack* called *Fortunate Richard*.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The main character leaves a smallish amount of money in his will, five lots of 100 *livres*, to collect interest over one, two, three, four or five full centuries, with the resulting astronomical sums to be spent on impossibly elaborate utopian projects.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin, who was 79 years old at the time, wrote thanking him for a great idea and telling him that he had decided to leave a bequest of 1,000 pounds each to his native Boston and his adopted Philadelphia.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] By 1990, more than $2,000,000 (~$4.23 million in 2024) had accumulated in Franklin's Philadelphia trust, which had loaned the money to local residents.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] From 1940 to 1990, the money was used mostly for mortgage loans.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] When the trust came due, Philadelphia decided to spend it on scholarships for local high school students.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's Boston trust fund accumulated almost $5,000,000 during that same time; at the end of its first 100 years a portion was allocated to help establish a trade school that became the Franklin Institute of Boston, and the entire fund was later dedicated to supporting this institute.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1787, a group of prominent ministers in Lancaster, Pennsylvania, proposed the foundation of a new college named in Franklin's honor.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin donated £200 towards the development of Franklin College (now called Franklin & Marshall College).
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] As the only person to have signed the Declaration of Independence in 1776, Treaty of Alliance with France in 1778, Treaty of Paris in 1783, and U.S.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Constitution in 1787, Franklin is considered one of the leading Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Since 1914, it has adorned American $100 bills.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] From 1948 to 1963, Franklin's portrait was on the half-dollar.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He has appeared on a $50 bill and on several varieties of the $100 bill from 1914 and 1918.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin also appears on the $1,000 Series EE savings bond.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] On April 12, 1976, as part of a bicentennial celebration, Congress dedicated a 20-foot (6 m) tall marble statue in Philadelphia's Franklin Institute as the Benjamin Franklin National Memorial.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Vice President Nelson Rockefeller presided over the dedication ceremony.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Many of Franklin's personal possessions are on display at the institute.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In London, his house at 36 Craven Street, which is the only surviving former residence of Franklin, was first marked with a blue plaque and has since been opened to the public as the Benjamin Franklin House.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1998, workmen restoring the building dug up the remains of six children and four adults hidden below the home.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] A total of 15 bodies have been recovered.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Friends of Benjamin Franklin House (the organization responsible for the restoration) note that the bones were likely placed there by William Hewson, who lived in the house for two years and who had built a small anatomy school at the back of the house.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] They note that while Franklin likely knew what Hewson was doing, he probably did not participate in any dissections because he was much more of a physicist than a medical man.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He has been honored on U.S. postage stamps many times.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] The image of Franklin, the first postmaster general of the United States, occurs on the face of U.S. postage more than any other American save that of George Washington.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] He appeared on the first U.S. postage stamp issued in 1847.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Post Office issued a series of postage stamps commonly referred to as the Washington–Franklin Issues, in which Washington and Franklin were depicted many times over a 14-year period, the longest run of any one series in U.S. postal history.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, he only appears on a few commemorative stamps.
[src:detonator/benjamin-franklin-p02] Some of the finest portrayals of Franklin on record can be found on the engravings inscribed on the face of U.S. postage.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] A **blasting machine** or **shot exploder** (commonly called a **plunger**) is a portable source of electric current to reliably fire a blasting cap to trigger a main explosive charge.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] It is mostly used in mining and demolition.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] The use of the term "machine" dates from early designs that used an electrical generator operated by winding a rotary handle or pushing down a T-handle.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] Modern blasting machines are battery-powered and operated by key switches and push-buttons, and do not resemble the older designs.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] The first satisfactory magnetic induction blasting machine was constructed in 1878 by Henry Julius Smith of Mountain View, New Jersey.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] Its mechanism consisted of a T-handle that was pushed down; the lower end of the handle was a rack that drove a pinion, which in turn drove a high-voltage magneto, which generated the high voltage that is required to detonate the blasting cap.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] A typical "capacitive discharge" blasting machine works by charging a capacitor from a battery, then discharging the capacitor through an external circuit, called the firing line, to fire the blasting cap.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] While the machine is idle, an "internal shunt" is connected across the output terminals so that any stray voltages induced in the external circuit, for example by nearby radio transmitters, are harmlessly short-circuited without triggering the blasting cap.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] The machines also typically include an "abort" feature to discharge the internal capacitor without firing the cap.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] Despite the older "T-Handle" design no longer being used, this design of blasting machine is most closely associated with *Looney Tunes*, and the character Wile E.
[src:detonator/blasting-machine] Coyote, due to his penchant for attempting to use explosive materials to capture or incapacitate the Road Runner, often ending in disaster for the Coyote as the explosive either backfires, the machine does not work properly, or the T-handle gets stuck.
[src:detonator/detonator] A **detonator** or **blasting cap** is a small explosive device or small quantity of explosive, which can be combined with a fuse, used for detonating a larger charge of high explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] Detonators come in a variety of types, depending on how they are initiated (chemically, mechanically, or electrically) and details of their inner working, which often involve several stages.
[src:detonator/detonator] Types of detonators include non-electric and electric.
[src:detonator/detonator] Non-electric detonators are typically stab or pyrotechnic while electric are typically "hot wire" (low voltage), exploding bridge wire (high voltage) or explosive foil (very high voltage).
[src:detonator/detonator] The original electric detonators invented in 1875 independently by Julius Smith and Perry Gardiner used mercury fulminate as the primary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] Around the turn of the century performance was enhanced in the Smith-Gardiner blasting cap by the addition of 10–20% potassium chlorate.
[src:detonator/detonator] This compound was superseded by others: lead azide, lead styphnate, some aluminium, or other materials such as DDNP to reduce the amount of lead emitted into the atmosphere by mining and quarrying operations.
[src:detonator/detonator] They also often use a small amount of TNT or tetryl in military detonators and PETN in commercial detonators.
[src:detonator/detonator] The first blasting cap or detonator was demonstrated in 1745 when British physician and apothecary William Watson showed that the electric spark of a friction machine could ignite black powder, by way of igniting a flammable substance mixed in with the black powder.
[src:detonator/detonator] In 1750, Benjamin Franklin in Philadelphia made a commercial blasting cap consisting of a paper tube full of black powder, with wires leading in both sides and wadding sealing up the ends.
[src:detonator/detonator] The two wires came close but did not touch, so a large electric spark discharge between the two wires would fire the cap.
[src:detonator/detonator] In 1832, a hot wire detonator was produced by American chemist Robert Hare, although attempts along similar lines had earlier been attempted by the Italians Volta and Cavallo.
[src:detonator/detonator] Hare constructed his blasting cap by passing a multistrand wire through a charge of gunpowder inside a tin tube; he had cut all but one fine strand of the multistrand wire so that the fine strand would serve as the hot bridgewire.
[src:detonator/detonator] When a strong current from a large battery (which he called a "deflagrator" or "calorimotor") was passed through the fine strand, it became incandescent and ignited the charge of gunpowder.
[src:detonator/detonator] In 1863, Alfred Nobel realized that although nitroglycerin could not be detonated by a fuse, it could be detonated by the explosion of a small charge of gunpowder, which in turn was ignited by a fuse.
[src:detonator/detonator] Within a year, he was adding mercury fulminate to the gunpowder charges of his detonators, and by 1867 he was using small copper capsules of mercury fulminate, triggered by a fuse, to detonate the nitroglycerin.
[src:detonator/detonator] In 1868, Henry Julius Smith of Boston introduced a cap that combined a spark gap ignitor and mercury fulminate, the first electric cap able to detonate dynamite.
[src:detonator/detonator] Gardner of North Adams, Massachusetts—developed electric detonators that combined a hot wire detonator with mercury fulminate explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] These were the first generally modern type blasting caps.
[src:detonator/detonator] Modern caps use different explosives and separate primary and secondary explosive charges, but are generally very similar to the Gardner and Smith caps.
[src:detonator/detonator] Smith also invented the first satisfactory portable power supply for igniting blasting caps: a high-voltage magneto that was driven by a rack and pinion, which in turn was driven by a T-handle that was pushed downwards.
[src:detonator/detonator] Electric match caps were developed in the early 1900s in Germany, and spread to the US in the 1950s when ICI International purchased the Atlas Powder Company, these match caps have become the predominant world standard cap type.
[src:detonator/detonator] The need for detonators such as blasting caps came from the development of safer secondary and tertiary explosives .
[src:detonator/detonator] Secondary and tertiary explosives are typically initiated by an explosives train starting with the detonator.
[src:detonator/detonator] For safety, detonators and the main explosive device are typically only joined just before use.
[src:detonator/detonator] 3. a small amount of a more powerful secondary explosive, directly in contact with the primary, called the "base" or "output" explosive, able to carry out the detonation through the casing of the detonator to the main explosive device to activate it.
[src:detonator/detonator] Explosives commonly used as the primary in detonators include lead azide, lead styphnate, tetryl, and DDNP.
[src:detonator/detonator] Early blasting caps also used silver fulminate, but it has been replaced with cheaper and safer primary explosives.
[src:detonator/detonator] Silver azide is still used sometimes, but very rarely due to its high price.
[src:detonator/detonator] It is possible to construct a Non Primary Explosive Detonator (NPED) in which the primary explosive is replaced by a flammable but non-explosive mixture that propagates a shock wave along a tube into the secondary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] NPEDs are harder to accidentally trigger by shock and can avoid the use of lead.
[src:detonator/detonator] As secondary "base" or "output" explosive, TNT or tetryl are typically found in military detonators and PETN in commercial detonators.
[src:detonator/detonator] Ordinary detonators usually take the form of ignition-based explosives.
[src:detonator/detonator] While they are mainly used in commercial operations, ordinary detonators are still used in military operations.
[src:detonator/detonator] This form of detonator is most commonly initiated using a safety fuse, and used in non time-critical detonations e.g. conventional munitions disposal.
[src:detonator/detonator] Well known detonators are lead azide [Pb(N3)2], silver azide [AgN3] and mercury fulminate [Hg(ONC)2].
[src:detonator/detonator] There are three categories of electrical detonators: instantaneous electrical detonators (IED), short period delay detonators (SPD) and long period delay detonators (LPD).
[src:detonator/detonator] SPDs are measured in milliseconds and LPDs are measured in seconds.
[src:detonator/detonator] In situations where nanosecond accuracy is required, specifically in the implosion charges in nuclear weapons, exploding-bridgewire detonators are employed.
[src:detonator/detonator] The initial shock wave is created by vaporizing a length of a thin wire by an electric discharge.
[src:detonator/detonator] A new development is a slapper detonator, which uses thin plates accelerated by an electrically exploded wire or foil to deliver the initial shock.
[src:detonator/detonator] It is in use in some modern weapons systems.
[src:detonator/detonator] A variant of this concept is used in mining operations, when the foil is exploded by a laser pulse delivered to the foil by optical fiber.
[src:detonator/detonator] A non-electric detonator is a shock tube detonator designed to initiate explosions, generally for the purpose of demolition of buildings and for use in the blasting of rock in mines and quarries.
[src:detonator/detonator] Instead of electric wires, a hollow plastic tube delivers the firing impulse to the detonator, making it immune to most of the hazards associated with stray electric current.
[src:detonator/detonator] It consists of a small diameter, three-layer plastic tube coated on the innermost wall with a reactive explosive compound, which, when ignited, propagates a low energy signal, similar to a dust explosion.
[src:detonator/detonator] The reaction travels at approximately 6,500 ft/s (2,000 m/s) along the length of the tubing with minimal disturbance outside of the tube.
[src:detonator/detonator] Non-electric detonators were invented by the Swedish company Nitro Nobel in the 1960s and 1970s, and launched to the demolitions market in 1973.
[src:detonator/detonator] In civil mining, electronic detonators have a better precision for delays.
[src:detonator/detonator] Electronic detonators are designed to provide the precise control necessary to produce accurate and consistent blasting results in a variety of blasting applications in the mining, quarrying, and construction industries.
[src:detonator/detonator] Electronic detonators may be programmed in millisecond or sub-millisecond increments using a dedicated programming device.
[src:detonator/detonator] Wireless electronic detonators are beginning to be available in the civil mining market.
[src:detonator/detonator] Encrypted radio signals are used to communicate the blast signal to each detonator at the correct time.
[src:detonator/detonator] While currently expensive, wireless detonators can enable new mining techniques as multiple blasts can be loaded at once and fired in sequence without putting humans in harm's way.
[src:detonator/detonator] A number 8 test blasting cap is one containing 2 grams of a mixture of 80 percent mercury fulminate and 20 percent potassium chlorate, or a blasting cap of equivalent strength.
[src:detonator/detonator] The oldest and simplest type of cap, fuse caps are a metal cylinder, closed at one end.
[src:detonator/detonator] From the open end inwards, there is first an empty space into which a pyrotechnic fuse is inserted and crimped, then a pyrotechnic ignition mix, a primary explosive, and then the main detonating explosive charge.
[src:detonator/detonator] The primary hazard of pyrotechnic blasting caps is that for proper usage, the fuse must be inserted and then crimped into place by crushing the base of the cap around the fuse.
[src:detonator/detonator] If the tool used to crimp the cap is used too close to the explosives, the primary explosive compound can detonate during crimping.
[src:detonator/detonator] A common hazardous practice is crimping caps with one's teeth; an accidental detonation can cause serious injury to the mouth.
[src:detonator/detonator] Fuse type blasting caps are still in active use today.
[src:detonator/detonator] They are the safest type to use around certain types of electromagnetic interference, and they have a built in time delay as the fuse burns down.
[src:detonator/detonator] Solid pack electric blasting caps use a thin bridgewire in direct contact (hence solid pack) with a primary explosive, which is heated by electric current and causes the detonation of the primary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] That primary explosive then detonates a larger charge of secondary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] Some solid pack fuses incorporate a small pyrotechnic delay element, up to a few hundred milliseconds, before the cap fires.
[src:detonator/detonator] Match type blasting caps use an electric match (insulating sheet with electrodes on both sides, a thin bridgewire soldered across the sides, all dipped in ignition and output mixes) to initiate the primary explosive, rather than direct contact between the bridgewire and the primary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] The match can be manufactured separately from the rest of the cap and only assembled at the end of the process.
[src:detonator/detonator] Match type caps are now the most common type found worldwide.
[src:detonator/detonator] The exploding-bridgewire detonator was invented in the 1940s as part of the Manhattan Project to develop nuclear weapons.
[src:detonator/detonator] The design goal was to produce a detonator which functioned very rapidly and predictably.
[src:detonator/detonator] Both Match and Solid Pack type electric caps take a few milliseconds to fire, as the bridgewire heats up and heats the explosive to the point of detonation.
[src:detonator/detonator] Exploding bridgewire or **EBW** detonators use a higher voltage electric charge and a very thin bridgewire, .04 inch long, .0016 inch diameter, (1 mm long, 0.04 mm diameter).
[src:detonator/detonator] Instead of heating up the explosive, the EBW detonator wire is heated so quickly by the high firing current that the wire actually vaporizes and explodes due to electric resistance heating.
[src:detonator/detonator] That electrically-driven explosion causes the low-density initiating explosive (usually PETN) to detonate, which in turn detonates a higher density secondary explosive (typically RDX or HMX) in many EBW designs.
[src:detonator/detonator] In addition to firing very quickly when properly initiated, EBW detonators are much safer than blasting caps from stray static electricity and other electric current.
[src:detonator/detonator] Enough current will melt the bridgewire, but it cannot detonate the initiator explosive without the full high-voltage high-current charge passing through the bridgewire.
[src:detonator/detonator] EBW detonators are used in many civilian applications where radio signals, static electricity, or other electrical hazards might cause accidents with conventional electric detonators.
[src:detonator/detonator] Exploding foil initiators (EFI), also known as Slapper detonators are an improvement on EBW detonators.
[src:detonator/detonator] Slappers, instead of directly using the exploding foil to detonate the initiator explosive, use the electrical vaporization of the foil to drive a small circle of insulating material such as PET film or kapton down a circular hole in an additional disc of insulating material.
[src:detonator/detonator] At the far end of that hole is a pellet of high-density secondary explosive.
[src:detonator/detonator] Slapper detonators omit the low-density initiating explosive used in EBW designs and they require much greater energy density than EBW detonators to function, making them inherently safer.
